        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>
                    <sic>Pittsburg</sic>
                </placeName>
                <date>Nov. 18<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Mr Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Pardon my encroachment on<lb/> your time when in a charitable
                occasion<lb/> I venture to impose a little on your good<lb/> nature. A few days
                before <date>New Years</date> a man<lb/> by the name of <persName>Levy</persName> a
                brother to <persName>Mrs Tobias</persName><lb/> came to our city in a very
                lamentable sick<lb/> condition. We have since taken every care<lb/> possible of him,
                but in spite of the best<lb/> attention and medical advice he <sic>lay's</sic>
                on<lb/> the brink of death, the doctors do not<lb/> suppose that he will be able to
                hold out<lb/> two days longer. We have written several<lb/> letters to <persName>Mr
                    Levy</persName> his brother in <placeName><sic>Chesnut</sic><lb/>
                    Sts.</placeName> but to his shame, he never answer<lb/> in to any of them. We
                therefore beg your<lb/> kind mediation with <persName>Mrs Tobias</persName> or
                her<lb/> brother that they may take pity on their poor<lb/> dying brother, he will
                hardly trouble them<lb/> much more in this world, since I believe<lb/> that before
                this will reach you, he may<lb/> be removed out of this vale of tears. Let them<lb/>
                consider <del>reflect</del> their own mortality and reflect<lb/> on the sad fate of
                their unfortunate brother.</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>His misfortune has caused us a great deal<lb/> of trouble and expense and his disease
                would<lb/> even <sic>dubble</sic> it. Our family and <persName>Mr.
                    Marcusson</persName><lb/> have been the only persons <sic>untill</sic> now
                who<lb/> visited him and endeavored to alleviate his<lb/> sufferings, and his
                burial, will of course<lb/> have to be done by us too.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I hope you will be kind enough to speak<lb/> to the above mentioned
                parties and soli-<lb/>city their assistance, and so oblige</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Yours Tr</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">very Respectfully</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <persName role="author">L Jarodawski</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
